# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hopcroft-karp-matching
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/berge-s-theorem] It was proven by French mathematician Claude Berge in 1957 (though already observed by Petersen in 1891 and Kőnig in 1931).
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/berge-s-theorem] To prove Berge's theorem, we first need a lemma.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/berge-s-theorem] Take a graph *G* and let *M* and *M′* be two matchings in *G*.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/berge-s-theorem] Let *G′* be the resultant graph from taking the symmetric difference of *M* and *M′*; i.e.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/berge-s-theorem] An even cycle whose edges alternate between *M* and *M′*.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/berge-s-theorem] A path whose edges alternate between *M* and *M′*, with distinct endpoints.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/berge-s-theorem] The lemma can be proven by observing that each vertex in *G′* can be incident to at most 2 edges: one from *M* and one from *M′*.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/berge-s-theorem] Graphs where every vertex has degree less than or equal to 2 must consist of either isolated vertices, cycles, and paths.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/berge-s-theorem] Furthermore, each path and cycle in *G′* must alternate between *M* and *M′*.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/berge-s-theorem] In order for a cycle to do this, it must have an equal number of edges from *M* and *M′*, and therefore be of even length.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/berge-s-theorem] Let us now prove the contrapositive of Berge's theorem: *G* has a matching larger than *M* if and only if *G* has an augmenting path.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/berge-s-theorem] Clearly, an augmenting path *P* of *G* can be used to produce a matching *M′* that is larger than *M* — just take *M′* to be the symmetric difference of *P* and *M* (*M′* contains exactly those edges of *G* that appear in exactly one of *P* and *M*).
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/berge-s-theorem] For the forward direction, let *M′* be a matching in *G* larger than *M*.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/berge-s-theorem] Consider *D*, the symmetric difference of *M* and *M′*.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/berge-s-theorem] Observe that *D* consists of paths and even cycles (as observed by the earlier lemma).
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/berge-s-theorem] Since *M′* is larger than *M*, *D* contains a component that has more edges from *M′* than *M*.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/berge-s-theorem] Such a component is a path in *G* that starts and ends with an edge from *M′*, so it is an augmenting path.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/berge-s-theorem] Let *M* be a maximum matching and consider an alternating chain such that the edges in the path alternates between being and not being in *M*.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/berge-s-theorem] If the alternating chain is a cycle or a path of even length starting on an unmatched vertex, then a new maximum matching *M′* can be found by interchanging the edges found in *M* and not in *M*.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/berge-s-theorem] For example, if the alternating chain is (*m*1, *n*1, *m*2, *n*2, ...), where *m*i ∈ *M* and *n*i ∉ *M*, interchanging them would make all *n*i part of the new matching and make all *m*i not part of the matching.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/berge-s-theorem] An edge is considered "free" if it belongs to a maximum matching but does not belong to all maximum matchings.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/berge-s-theorem] An edge *e* is free if and only if, in an arbitrary maximum matching *M*, edge *e* belongs to an even alternating path starting at an unmatched vertex or to an alternating cycle.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/berge-s-theorem] By the first corollary, if edge *e* is part of such an alternating chain, then a new maximum matching, *M′*, must exist and *e* would exist either in *M* or *M′*, and therefore be free.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/berge-s-theorem] Conversely, if edge *e* is free, then *e* is in some maximum matching *M* but not in *M′*.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/berge-s-theorem] Since *e* is not part of both *M* and *M′*, it must still exist after taking the symmetric difference of *M* and *M′*.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/berge-s-theorem] The symmetric difference of *M* and *M′* results in a graph consisting of isolated vertices, even alternating cycles, and alternating paths.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/berge-s-theorem] Suppose to the contrary that *e* belongs to some odd-length path component.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/berge-s-theorem] But then one of *M* and *M′* must have one fewer edge than the other in this component, meaning that the component as a whole is an augmenting path with respect to that matching.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/berge-s-theorem] By the original lemma, then, that matching (whether *M* or *M′*) cannot be a maximum matching, which contradicts the assumption that both *M* and *M′* are maximum.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/berge-s-theorem] So, since *e* cannot belong to any odd-length path component, it must either be in an alternating cycle or an even-length alternating path.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] In the mathematical field of graph theory, a **bipartite graph** (or **bigraph**) is a graph whose vertices can be divided into two disjoint and independent sets U and V , that is, every edge connects a vertex in U to one in V .
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] Vertex sets U and V are usually called the *parts* of the graph.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] Equivalently, a bipartite graph is a graph that does not contain any odd-length cycles.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] The two sets U and V may be thought of as a coloring of the graph with two colors: if one colors all nodes in U blue, and all nodes in V red, each edge has endpoints of differing colors, as is required in the graph coloring problem.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] In contrast, such a coloring is impossible in the case of a non-bipartite graph, such as a triangle: after one node is colored blue and another red, the third vertex of the triangle is connected to vertices of both colors, preventing it from being assigned either color.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] One often writes $G=(U,V,E)$ to denote a bipartite graph whose partition has the parts U and V , with E denoting the edges of the graph.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] If a bipartite graph is not connected, it may have more than one bipartition; in this case, the $(U,V,E)$ notation is helpful in specifying one particular bipartition that may be of importance in an application.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] If $|U|=|V|$ , that is, if the two subsets have equal cardinality, then G is called a *balanced* bipartite graph.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] If all vertices on the same side of the bipartition have the same degree, then G is called biregular.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] When modelling relations between two different classes of objects, bipartite graphs very often arise naturally.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] For instance, a graph of football players and clubs, with an edge between a player and a club if the player has played for that club, is a natural example of an *affiliation network*, a type of bipartite graph used in social network analysis.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] This problem can be modeled as a dominating set problem in a bipartite graph that has a vertex for each train and each station and an edge for each pair of a station and a train that stops at that station.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] In bipartite graphs, the size of minimum vertex cover is equal to the size of the maximum matching; this is Kőnig's theorem.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] An alternative and equivalent form of this theorem is that the size of the maximum independent set plus the size of the maximum matching is equal to the number of vertices.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] In any graph without isolated vertices the size of the minimum edge cover plus the size of a maximum matching equals the number of vertices.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] Combining this equality with Kőnig's theorem leads to the facts that, in bipartite graphs, the size of the minimum edge cover is equal to the size of the maximum independent set, and the size of the minimum edge cover plus the size of the minimum vertex cover is equal to the number of vertices.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] Another class of related results concerns perfect graphs: every bipartite graph, the complement of every bipartite graph, the line graph of every bipartite graph, and the complement of the line graph of every bipartite graph, are all perfect.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] Perfection of bipartite graphs is easy to see (their chromatic number is two and their maximum clique size is also two) but perfection of the complements of bipartite graphs is less trivial, and is another restatement of Kőnig's theorem.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] This was one of the results that motivated the initial definition of perfect graphs.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] The bipartite graphs, line graphs of bipartite graphs, and their complements form four out of the five basic classes of perfect graphs used in the proof of the strong perfect graph theorem.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] It follows that any subgraph of a bipartite graph is also bipartite because it cannot gain an odd cycle.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] For a vertex, the number of adjacent vertices is called the degree of the vertex and is denoted $\deg v$ .
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] The degree sequence of a bipartite graph is the pair of lists each containing the degrees of the two parts U and V .
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] Isomorphic bipartite graphs have the same degree sequence.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] However, the degree sequence does not, in general, uniquely identify a bipartite graph; in some cases, non-isomorphic bipartite graphs may have the same degree sequence.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] The bipartite realization problem is the problem of finding a simple bipartite graph with the degree sequence being two given lists of natural numbers.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] The biadjacency matrix of a bipartite graph $(U,V,E)$ is a (0,1) matrix of size $|U|\times |V|$ that has a one for each pair of adjacent vertices and a zero for nonadjacent vertices.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] Biadjacency matrices may be used to describe equivalences between bipartite graphs, hypergraphs, and directed graphs.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] A hypergraph is a combinatorial structure that, like an undirected graph, has vertices and edges, but in which the edges may be arbitrary sets of vertices rather than having to have exactly two endpoints.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] A bipartite graph $(U,V,E)$ may be used to model a hypergraph in which U is the set of vertices of the hypergraph, V is the set of hyperedges, and E contains an edge from a hypergraph vertex v to a hypergraph edge e exactly when v is one of the endpoints of e.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] Under this correspondence, the biadjacency matrices of bipartite graphs are exactly the incidence matrices of the corresponding hypergraphs.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] A similar reinterpretation of adjacency matrices may be used to show a one-to-one correspondence between directed graphs (on a given number of labeled vertices, allowing self-loops) and balanced bipartite graphs, with the same number of vertices on both sides of the bipartition.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] For, the adjacency matrix of a directed graph with n vertices can be any (0,1) matrix of size $n\times n$ , which can then be reinterpreted as the adjacency matrix of a bipartite graph with n vertices on each side of its bipartition.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] In this construction, the bipartite graph is the bipartite double cover of the directed graph.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] It is possible to test whether a graph is bipartite, and to return either a two-coloring (if it is bipartite) or an odd cycle (if it is not) in linear time, using depth-first search (DFS).
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] The main idea is to assign to each vertex the color that differs from the color of its parent in the DFS forest, assigning colors in a preorder traversal of the depth-first-search forest.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] This will necessarily provide a two-coloring of the spanning forest consisting of the edges connecting vertices to their parents, but it may not properly color some of the non-forest edges.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] In a DFS forest, one of the two endpoints of every non-forest edge is an ancestor of the other endpoint, and when the depth first search discovers an edge of this type it should check that these two vertices have different colors.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] If they do not, then the path in the forest from ancestor to descendant, together with the miscolored edge, form an odd cycle, which is returned from the algorithm together with the result that the graph is not bipartite.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] However, if the algorithm terminates without detecting an odd cycle of this type, then every edge must be properly colored, and the algorithm returns the coloring together with the result that the graph is bipartite.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] Alternatively, a similar procedure may be used with breadth-first search in place of DFS.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] Again, each node is given the opposite color to its parent in the search forest, in breadth-first order.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] If, when a vertex is colored, there exists an edge connecting it to a previously-colored vertex with the same color, then this edge together with the paths in the breadth-first search forest connecting its two endpoints to their lowest common ancestor forms an odd cycle.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] If the algorithm terminates without finding an odd cycle in this way, then it must have found a proper coloring, and can safely conclude that the graph is bipartite.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] Odd cycle transversal is an NP-complete algorithmic problem that asks, given a graph *G* = (*V*,*E*) and a number *k*, whether there exists a set of *k* vertices whose removal from *G* would cause the resulting graph to be bipartite.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] The problem is fixed-parameter tractable, meaning that there is an algorithm whose running time can be bounded by a polynomial function of the size of the graph multiplied by a larger function of *k*.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] The name *odd cycle transversal* comes from the fact that a graph is bipartite if and only if it has no odd cycles.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] Hence, to delete vertices from a graph in order to obtain a bipartite graph, one needs to "hit all odd cycle", or find a so-called odd cycle transversal set.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] In the illustration, every odd cycle in the graph contains the blue (the bottommost) vertices, so removing those vertices kills all odd cycles and leaves a bipartite graph.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] The *edge bipartization* problem is the algorithmic problem of deleting as few edges as possible to make a graph bipartite and is also an important problem in graph modification algorithmics.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] This problem is also fixed-parameter tractable, and can be solved in time ${\textstyle O\left(2^{k}m^{2}\right)}$ , where *k* is the number of edges to delete and *m* is the number of edges in the input graph.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] A matching in a graph is a subset of its edges, no two of which share an endpoint.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] Polynomial time algorithms are known for many algorithmic problems on matchings, including maximum matching (finding a matching that uses as many edges as possible), maximum-weight matching, and stable marriage.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] In many cases, matching problems are simpler to solve on bipartite graphs than on non-bipartite graphs, and many matching algorithms such as the Hopcroft–Karp algorithm for maximum-cardinality matching work correctly only on bipartite inputs.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] As a simple example, suppose that a set P of people are all seeking jobs from among a set J of jobs, with not all people suitable for all jobs.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] This situation can be modeled as a bipartite graph $(P,J,E)$ where an edge connects each job-seeker with each suitable job.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] A perfect matching describes a way of simultaneously satisfying all job-seekers and filling all jobs; Hall's marriage theorem provides a characterization of the bipartite graphs which allow perfect matchings.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] The National Resident Matching Program applies graph matching methods to solve this problem for U.S. medical student job-seekers and hospital residency jobs.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] The Dulmage–Mendelsohn decomposition is a structural decomposition of bipartite graphs that is useful in finding maximum matchings.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] Bipartite graphs are extensively used in modern coding theory, especially to decode codewords received from the channel.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] Factor graphs and Tanner graphs are examples of this.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] A Tanner graph is a bipartite graph in which the vertices on one side of the bipartition represent digits of a codeword, and the vertices on the other side represent combinations of digits that are expected to sum to zero in a codeword without errors.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] A factor graph is a closely related belief network used for probabilistic decoding of LDPC and turbo codes.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] In computer science, a Petri net is a mathematical modeling tool used in analysis and simulations of concurrent systems.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] A system is modeled as a bipartite directed graph with two sets of nodes: A set of "place" nodes that contain resources, and a set of "event" nodes which generate and/or consume resources.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] There are additional constraints on the nodes and edges that constrain the behavior of the system.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] Petri nets utilize the properties of bipartite directed graphs and other properties to allow mathematical proofs of the behavior of systems while also allowing easy implementation of simulations of the system.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] In projective geometry, Levi graphs are a form of bipartite graph used to model the incidences between points and lines in a configuration.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/bipartite-graph] Corresponding to the geometric property of points and lines that every two lines meet in at most one point and every two points be connected with a single line, Levi graphs necessarily do not contain any cycles of length four, so their girth must be six or more.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] It runs in $O(|E|{\sqrt {|V|}})$ time in the worst case, where E is set of edges in the graph, V is set of vertices of the graph, and it is assumed that $|E|=\Omega (|V|)$ .
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] In the case of dense graphs the time bound becomes $O(|V|^{2.5})$ , and for sparse random graphs it runs in time $O(|E|\log |V|)$ with high probability.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] The algorithm was discovered by John Hopcroft and Richard Karp (1973) and independently by Alexander Karzanov (1973).
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] As in previous methods for matching such as the Hungarian algorithm and the work of Edmonds (1965), the Hopcroft–Karp algorithm repeatedly increases the size of a partial matching by finding *augmenting paths*.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] These paths are sequences of edges of the graph, which alternate between edges in the matching and edges out of the partial matching, and where the initial and final edge are not in the partial matching.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] Finding an augmenting path allows us to increment the size of the partial matching, by simply toggling the edges of the augmenting path (putting in the partial matching those that were not, and vice versa).
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] The same performance of $O(|E|{\sqrt {|V|}})$ can be achieved to find maximum-cardinality matchings in arbitrary graphs, with the more complicated algorithm of Micali and Vazirani.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] The Hopcroft–Karp algorithm can be seen as a special case of Dinic's algorithm for the maximum-flow problem.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] A vertex that is not the endpoint of an edge in some partial matching M is called a *free vertex*.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] The basic concept that the algorithm relies on is that of an *augmenting path*, a path that starts at a free vertex, ends at a free vertex, and alternates between unmatched and matched edges within the path.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] It follows from this definition that, except for the endpoints, all other vertices (if any) in augmenting path must be non-free vertices.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] An augmenting path could consist of only two vertices (both free) and single unmatched edge between them.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] If M is a matching, and P is an augmenting path relative to M , then the symmetric difference of the two sets of edges, $M\oplus P$ , would form a matching with size $|M|+1$ .
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] Thus, by finding augmenting paths, an algorithm may increase the size of the matching.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] Conversely, suppose that a matching M is not optimal, and let P be the symmetric difference $M\oplus M^{*}$ where $M^{*}$ is an optimal matching.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] Because M and $M^{*}$ are both matchings, every vertex has degree at most 2 in P .
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] So P must form a collection of disjoint cycles, of paths with an equal number of matched and unmatched edges in M , of augmenting paths for M , and of augmenting paths for $M^{*}$ ; but the latter is impossible because $M^{*}$ is optimal.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] Now, the cycles and the paths with equal numbers of matched and unmatched vertices do not contribute to the difference in size between M and $M^{*}$ , so this difference is equal to the number of augmenting paths for M in P .
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] Thus, whenever there exists a matching $M^{*}$ larger than the current matching M , there must also exist an augmenting path.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] If no augmenting path can be found, an algorithm may safely terminate, since in this case M must be optimal.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] An augmenting path in a matching problem is closely related to the augmenting paths arising in maximum flow problems, paths along which one may increase the amount of flow between the terminals of the flow.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] It is possible to transform the bipartite matching problem into a maximum flow instance, such that the alternating paths of the matching problem become augmenting paths of the flow problem.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] It suffices to insert two vertices, source and sink, and insert edges of unit capacity from the source to each vertex in U , and from each vertex in V to the sink; and let edges from U to V have unit capacity.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] A generalization of the technique used in Hopcroft–Karp algorithm to find maximum flow in an arbitrary network is known as Dinic's algorithm.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] The algorithm may be expressed in the following pseudocode.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] In more detail, let U and V be the two sets in the bipartition of G , and let the matching from U to V at any time be represented as the set M .
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] Each phase consists of the following steps.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] The algorithm terminates when no more augmenting paths are found by the breadth first search step of one of the phases.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] Each phase consists of a single breadth first search and a single depth-first search.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] Thus, a single phase may be implemented in $O(|E|)$ time.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] Therefore, the first ${\sqrt {|V|}}$ phases, in a graph with $|V|$ vertices and $|E|$ edges, take time $O(|E|{\sqrt {|V|}})$ .
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] Each phase increases the length of the shortest augmenting path by at least one: the phase finds a maximal set of augmenting paths of the given length, so any remaining augmenting path must be longer.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] Therefore, once the initial ${\sqrt {|V|}}$ phases of the algorithm are complete, the shortest remaining augmenting path has at least ${\sqrt {|V|}}$ edges in it.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] However, the symmetric difference of the eventual optimal matching and of the partial matching *M* found by the initial phases forms a collection of vertex-disjoint augmenting paths and alternating cycles.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] If each of the paths in this collection has length at least ${\sqrt {|V|}}$ , there can be at most ${\sqrt {|V|}}$ paths in the collection, and the size of the optimal matching can differ from the size of M by at most ${\sqrt {|V|}}$ edges.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] Since each phase of the algorithm increases the size of the matching by at least one, there can be at most ${\sqrt {|V|}}$ additional phases before the algorithm terminates.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] Since the algorithm performs a total of at most $2{\sqrt {|V|}}$ phases, it takes a total time of $O(|E|{\sqrt {|V|}})$ in the worst case.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] In many instances, however, the time taken by the algorithm may be even faster than this worst-case analysis indicates.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] For instance, in the average case for sparse bipartite random graphs, Bast et al.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] (2006) (improving a previous result of Motwani 1994) showed that with high probability all non-optimal matchings have augmenting paths of logarithmic length.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] As a consequence, for these graphs, the Hopcroft–Karp algorithm takes $O(\log |V|)$ phases and $O(|E|\log |V|)$ total time.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] For sparse graphs, the Hopcroft–Karp algorithm continues to have the best known worst-case performance, but for dense graphs ( $|E|=\Omega (|V|^{2})$ ) a more recent algorithm by Alt et al.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] Their algorithm is based on using a push-relabel maximum flow algorithm and then, when the matching created by this algorithm becomes close to optimum, switching to the Hopcroft–Karp method.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] Several authors have performed experimental comparisons of bipartite matching algorithms.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] Their results in general tend to show that the Hopcroft–Karp method is not as good in practice as it is in theory: it is outperformed both by simpler breadth-first and depth-first strategies for finding augmenting paths, and by push-relabel techniques.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] The same idea of finding a maximal set of shortest augmenting paths works also for finding maximum cardinality matchings in non-bipartite graphs, and for the same reasons the algorithms based on this idea take $O({\sqrt {|V|}})$ phases.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] However, for non-bipartite graphs, the task of finding the augmenting paths within each phase is more difficult.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] Building on the work of several slower predecessors, Micali & Vazirani (1980) showed how to implement a phase in linear time, resulting in a non-bipartite matching algorithm with the same time bound as the Hopcroft–Karp algorithm for bipartite graphs.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] The Micali–Vazirani technique is complex, and its authors did not provide full proofs of their results; subsequently, a "clear exposition" was published by Peterson & Loui (1988) and alternative methods were described by other authors.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] In 2012, Vazirani offered a new simplified proof of the Micali-Vazirani algorithm.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] Let the vertices of our graph be partitioned in `U` and `V`, and consider a partial matching, as indicated by the `Pair_U` and `Pair_V` tables that contain the one vertex to which each vertex of `U` and of `V` is matched, or `NIL` for unmatched vertices.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] The key idea is to add two dummy vertices on each side of the graph: uDummy connected to all unmatched vertices in `U` and vDummy connected to all unmatched vertices in `V`.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] Now, if we run a breadth-first search (BFS) from uDummy to vDummy then we can get the paths of minimal length that connect currently unmatched vertices in `U` to currently unmatched vertices in `V`.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] Note that, as the graph is bipartite, these paths always alternate between vertices in `U` and vertices in `V`, and we require in our BFS that when going from `V` to `U`, we always select a matched edge.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] If we reach an unmatched vertex of `V`, then we end at vDummy and the search for paths in the BFS terminate.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] Observe in particular that BFS marks the unmatched nodes of `U` with distance 0, then increments the distance every time it comes back to `U`.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] This guarantees that the paths considered in the BFS are of minimal length to connect unmatched vertices of `U` to unmatched vertices of `V` while always going back from `V` to `U` on edges that are currently part of the matching.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] In particular, the special `NIL` vertex, which corresponds to vDummy, then gets assigned a finite distance, so the BFS function returns true iff some path has been found.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] If no path has been found, then there are no augmenting paths left and the matching is maximal.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] If BFS returns true, then we can go ahead and update the pairing for vertices on the minimal-length paths found from `U` to `V`: we do so using a depth-first search (DFS).
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] Note that each vertex in `V` on such a path, except for the last one, is currently matched.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] So we can explore with the DFS, making sure that the paths that we follow correspond to the distances computed in the BFS.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] This is same as replacing the current matching by the symmetric difference between the current matching and the entire path..
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] Note that the code ensures that all augmenting paths that we consider are vertex disjoint.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] Indeed, after doing the symmetric difference for a path, none of its vertices could be considered again in the DFS, just because the `Dist[Pair_V[v]]` will not be equal to `Dist[u] + 1` (it would be exactly `Dist[u]`).
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] Also observe that the DFS does not visit the same vertex multiple times.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] When we were not able to find any shortest augmenting path from a vertex `u`, then the DFS marks vertex `u` by setting `Dist[u]` to infinity, so that these vertices are not visited again.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] One last observation is that we actually don't need uDummy: its role is simply to put all unmatched vertices of `U` in the queue when we start the BFS.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/hopcroft-karp-algorithm] As for vDummy, it is denoted as `NIL` in the pseudocode above.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] In the mathematical area of graph theory, **Kőnig's theorem**, proved by Dénes Kőnig (1931), describes an equivalence between the maximum matching problem and the minimum vertex cover problem in bipartite graphs.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] It was discovered independently, also in 1931, by Jenő Egerváry in the more general case of weighted graphs.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] A vertex cover in a graph is a set of vertices that includes at least one endpoint of every edge, and a vertex cover is *minimum* if no other vertex cover has fewer vertices.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] A matching in a graph is a set of edges no two of which share an endpoint, and a matching is *maximum* if no other matching has more edges.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] It is obvious from the definition that any vertex-cover set must be at least as large as any matching set (since for every edge in the matching, at least one vertex is needed in the cover).
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] In particular, the minimum vertex cover set is at least as large as the maximum matching set.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Kőnig's theorem states that, in any bipartite graph, the minimum vertex cover set and the maximum matching set have in fact the same size.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] The bipartite graph shown in the above illustration has 14 vertices; a matching with six edges is shown in blue, and a vertex cover with six vertices is shown in red.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] There can be no smaller vertex cover, because any vertex cover has to include at least one endpoint of each matched edge (as well as of every other edge), so this is a minimum vertex cover.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Similarly, there can be no larger matching, because any matched edge has to include at least one endpoint in the vertex cover, so this is a maximum matching.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Kőnig's theorem states that the equality between the sizes of the matching and the cover (in this example, both numbers are six) applies more generally to any bipartite graph.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] The following proof provides a way of constructing a minimum vertex cover from a maximum matching.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Let $G=(V,E)$ be a bipartite graph and let $A,B$ be the two parts of the vertex set V .
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Suppose that M is a maximum matching for G .
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Construct the flow network $G'_{\infty }$ derived from G in such way that there are edges of capacity 1 from the source s to every vertex $a\in A$ and from every vertex $b\in B$ to the sink t , and of capacity $+\infty$ from a to b for any $(a,b)\in E$ .
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] The size $|M|$ of the maximum matching in G is the size of a maximum flow in $G'_{\infty }$ , which, in turn, is the size of a minimum cut in the network $G'_{\infty }$ , as follows from the max-flow min-cut theorem.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Then the minimum cut is composed only of edges going from s to $A_{T}$ or from $B_{S}$ to t , as any edge from $A_{S}$ to $B_{T}$ would make the size of the cut infinite.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Therefore, the size of the minimum cut is equal to $|A_{T}|+|B_{S}|$ .
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] On the other hand, $A_{T}\cup B_{S}$ is a vertex cover, as any edge that is not incident to vertices from $A_{T}$ and $B_{S}$ must be incident to a pair of vertices from $A_{S}$ and $B_{T}$ , which would contradict the fact that there are no edges between $A_{S}$ and $B_{T}$ .
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Thus, $A_{T}\cup B_{S}$ is a minimum vertex cover of G .
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] No vertex in a vertex cover can cover more than one edge of M (because the edge half-overlap would prevent M from being a matching in the first place), so if a vertex cover with $|M|$ vertices can be constructed, it must be a minimum cover.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] To construct such a cover, let U be the set of unmatched vertices in A (possibly empty), and let Z be the set of vertices that are either in U or are connected to U by alternating paths (paths that alternate between edges that are in the matching and edges that are not in the matching).
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Every edge e in E either belongs to an alternating path (and has a right endpoint in K ), or it has a left endpoint in K .
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] For, if e is matched but not in an alternating path, then its left endpoint cannot be in an alternating path (because two matched edges can not share a vertex) and thus belongs to $A\setminus Z$ .
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Alternatively, if e is unmatched but not in an alternating path, then its left endpoint cannot be in an alternating path, for such a path could be extended by adding e to it.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Additionally, every vertex in K is an endpoint of a matched edge.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] For, every vertex in $A\setminus Z$ is matched because Z is a superset of U , the set of unmatched left vertices.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] And every vertex in $B\cap Z$ must also be matched, for if there existed an alternating path to an unmatched vertex then changing the matching by removing the matched edges from this path and adding the unmatched edges in their place would increase the size of the matching.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] However, no matched edge can have both of its endpoints in K .
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Thus, K is a vertex cover of cardinality equal to M , and must be a minimum vertex cover.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Similarly we define a fractional vertex-cover - an assignment of a non-negative weight to each vertex, such that the sum of weights in each edge is at least 1 (an integral vertex-cover is a special case of a fractional vertex-cover in which the weights are in {0,1}).
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] where **x** is a vector of size |*E*| in which each element represents the weight of an edge in the fractional matching.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] **1**E is a vector of |*E*| ones, so the first line indicates the size of the matching.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] **0***E* is a vector of |*E*| zeros, so the second line indicates the constraint that the weights are non-negative.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] **1**V is a vector of |*V*| ones and **A***G* is the incidence matrix of *G,* so the third line indicates the constraint that the sum of weights near each vertex is at most 1.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] where **y** is a vector of size |V| in which each element represents the weight of a vertex in the fractional cover.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Here, the first line is the size of the cover, the second line represents the non-negativity of the weights, and the third line represents the requirement that the sum of weights near each edge must be at least 1.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Now, the minimum fractional cover LP is exactly the dual linear program of the maximum fractional matching LP.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Therefore, by the LP duality theorem, both programs have the same solution.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] What makes bipartite graphs special is that, in bipartite graphs, both these linear programs have optimal solutions in which all variable values are integers.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] This follows from the fact that in the fractional matching polytope of a bipartite graph, all extreme points have only integer coordinates, and the same is true for the fractional vertex-cover polytope.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] The constructive proof described above provides an algorithm for producing a minimum vertex cover given a maximum matching.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Thus, the Hopcroft–Karp algorithm for finding maximum matchings in bipartite graphs may also be used to solve the vertex cover problem efficiently in these graphs.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Despite the equivalence of the two problems from the point of view of exact solutions, they are not equivalent for approximation algorithms.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Bipartite maximum matchings can be approximated arbitrarily accurately in constant time by distributed algorithms; in contrast, approximating the minimum vertex cover of a bipartite graph requires at least logarithmic time.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] In the graph shown in the introduction take L to be the set of vertices in the bottom layer of the diagram and R to be the set of vertices in the top layer of the diagram.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] From left to right label the vertices in the bottom layer with the numbers 1, ..., 7 and label the vertices in the top layer with the numbers 8, ..., 14.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] The set U of unmatched vertices from L is {1}.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] For graphs that are not bipartite, the minimum vertex cover may be larger than the maximum matching.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Moreover, the two problems are very different in complexity: maximum matchings can be found in polynomial time for any graph, while minimum vertex cover is NP-complete.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] The complement of a vertex cover in any graph is an independent set, so a minimum vertex cover is complementary to a maximum independent set; finding maximum independent sets is another NP-complete problem.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] The equivalence between matching and covering articulated in Kőnig's theorem allows minimum vertex covers and maximum independent sets to be computed in polynomial time for bipartite graphs, despite the NP-completeness of these problems for more general graph families.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Kőnig's theorem is named after the Hungarian mathematician Dénes Kőnig.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] However, Bondy & Murty (1976) attribute Kőnig's theorem itself to a later paper of Kőnig (1931).
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] According to Biggs, Lloyd & Wilson (1976), Kőnig attributed the idea of studying matchings in bipartite graphs to his father, mathematician Gyula Kőnig.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] In Hungarian, Kőnig's name has a double acute accent, but his theorem is sometimes spelled (incorrectly) in German characters, with an umlaut.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Kőnig's theorem is equivalent to many other min-max theorems in graph theory and combinatorics, such as Hall's marriage theorem and Dilworth's theorem.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Since bipartite matching is a special case of maximum flow, the theorem also results from the max-flow min-cut theorem.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] A graph is said to be perfect if, in every induced subgraph, the chromatic number equals the size of the largest clique.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Any bipartite graph is perfect, because each of its subgraphs is either bipartite or independent; in a bipartite graph that is not independent the chromatic number and the size of the largest clique are both two while in an independent set the chromatic number and clique number are both one.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] A graph is perfect if and only if its complement is perfect, and Kőnig's theorem can be seen as equivalent to the statement that the complement of a bipartite graph is perfect.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Conversely, Kőnig's theorem proves the perfection of the complements of bipartite graphs, a result proven in a more explicit form by Gallai (1958).
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] One can also connect Kőnig's line coloring theorem to a different class of perfect graphs, the line graphs of bipartite graphs.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] If *G* is a graph, the line graph *L*(*G*) has a vertex for each edge of *G*, and an edge for each pair of adjacent edges in *G*.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Thus, the chromatic number of *L*(*G*) equals the chromatic index of *G*.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] If *G* is bipartite, the cliques in *L*(*G*) are exactly the sets of edges in *G* sharing a common endpoint.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Now Kőnig's line coloring theorem, stating that the chromatic index equals the maximum vertex degree in any bipartite graph, can be interpreted as stating that the line graph of a bipartite graph is perfect.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Since line graphs of bipartite graphs are perfect, the complements of line graphs of bipartite graphs are also perfect.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] A clique in the complement of the line graph of *G* is just a matching in *G*.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] And a coloring in the complement of the line graph of *G*, when *G* is bipartite, is a partition of the edges of *G* into subsets of edges sharing a common endpoint; the endpoints shared by each of these subsets form a vertex cover for *G*.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Therefore, Kőnig's theorem itself can also be interpreted as stating that the complements of line graphs of bipartite graphs are perfect.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Konig's theorem can be extended to weighted graphs.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] Jenő Egerváry (1931) considered graphs in which each edge *e* has a non-negative integer weight *we*.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] The **w-***weight of a matching* is the sum of weights of the edges participating in the matching.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] A ***w-**vertex-cover* is a multiset of vertices ("multiset" means that each vertex may appear several times), in which each edge *e* is adjacent to at least *we* vertices.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] As in the proof of Konig's theorem, the LP duality theorem implies that the optimal values are equal (for any graph), and the fact that the graph is bipartite implies that these programs have optimal solutions in which all values are integers.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] One can consider a graph in which each vertex *v* has a non-negative integer weight *bv*.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] The ***b**-weight* of a vertex-cover is the sum of *bv* for all *v* in the cover.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/könig-s-theorem-graph-theory] A ***b**-matching* is an assignment of a non-negative integral weight to each edge, such that the sum of weights of edges adjacent to any vertex *v* is at most *bv*.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] In the mathematical discipline of graph theory, a **matching** or **independent edge set** in an undirected graph is a set of edges without common vertices.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] In other words, a subset of the edges is a matching if each vertex appears in at most one edge of that matching.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] Finding a largest matching in a bipartite graph can be treated as a network flow problem.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] Finding a largest matching in a general graph is much more difficult; it can be done using Edmonds' blossom algorithm.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] Given a graph *G* = (*V*, *E*), a **matching** *M* in *G* is a set of pairwise non-adjacent edges, none of which are loops; that is, no two edges share common vertices.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] M is a matching *of* $U\subseteq V$ if every vertex in U is incident with an edge in M .
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] A vertex is **matched** (or **saturated**) if it is an endpoint of one of the edges in the matching.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] Otherwise the vertex is **unmatched** (or **unsaturated**).
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] A **maximal matching** is a matching *M* of a graph *G* that is not a subset of any other matching.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] A matching *M* of a graph *G* is maximal if every edge in *G* has a non-empty intersection with at least one edge in *M*.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] The following figure shows examples of maximal matchings (red) in three graphs.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] A **maximum matching** (also known as maximum-cardinality matching) is a matching that contains the largest possible number of edges.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] The **matching number** $\nu (G)$ of a graph G is the size of a maximum matching.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] Every maximum matching is maximal, but not every maximal matching is a maximum matching.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] The following figure shows examples of maximum matchings in the same three graphs.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] A **perfect matching** is a matching that matches all vertices of the graph.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] That is, a matching is perfect if every vertex of the graph is incident to an edge of the matching.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] Every perfect matching is maximum and hence maximal.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] In some literature, the term **complete matching** is used.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] In the above figure, only part (b) shows a perfect matching.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] A perfect matching is also a minimum-size edge cover.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] Thus, the size of a maximum matching is no larger than the size of a minimum edge cover: ⁠ $\nu (G)\leq \rho (G)$ ⁠.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] A graph can only contain a perfect matching when the graph has an even number of vertices.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] A **near-perfect matching** is one in which exactly one vertex is unmatched.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] Clearly, a graph can only contain a near-perfect matching when the graph has an odd number of vertices, and near-perfect matchings are maximum matchings.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] In the above figure, part (c) shows a near-perfect matching.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] If every vertex is unmatched by some near-perfect matching, then the graph is called factor-critical.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] An **induced matching** is a matching that is the edge set of an induced subgraph.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] Given a matching *M*, an **alternating path** is a path that begins with an unmatched vertex and whose edges belong alternately to the matching and not to the matching.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] An **augmenting path** is an alternating path that starts from and ends on free (unmatched) vertices.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] Berge's lemma states that a matching *M* is maximum if and only if there is no augmenting path with respect to M *.* Using Berge's lemma, we can start from any matching M and repeatedly apply augmenting paths until no more augmenting paths are found.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] This reduces the problem of finding a large matching to finding augmented paths.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] In any graph without isolated vertices, the sum of the matching number and the edge covering number equals the number of vertices.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] If there is a perfect matching, then both the matching number and the edge cover number are |*V* | / 2.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] Kőnig's theorem states that, in bipartite graphs, the maximum matching is equal in size to the minimum vertex cover.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] Via this result, the minimum vertex cover, maximum independent set, and maximum vertex biclique problems may be solved in polynomial time for bipartite graphs.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] Hall's marriage theorem provides a characterization of bipartite graphs which have a perfect matching and Tutte's theorem on perfect matchings provides a characterization for arbitrary graphs.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] A spectral characterization of the matching number of a graph is given by Hassani Monfared and Mallik as follows: Let G be a graph on n vertices, and $\lambda _{1}>\lambda _{2}>\ldots >\lambda _{k}>0$ be k distinct nonzero purely imaginary numbers where $2k\leq n$ .
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] Then the matching number of G is k if and only if (a) there is a real skew-symmetric matrix A with graph G and eigenvalues $\pm \lambda _{1},\pm \lambda _{2},\ldots ,\pm \lambda _{k}$ and $n-2k$ zeros, and (b) all real skew-symmetric matrices with graph G have at most $2k$ nonzero eigenvalues.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] Note that the (simple) graph of a real symmetric or skew-symmetric matrix A of order n has n vertices and edges given by the nonozero off-diagonal entries of A .
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] In particular, this shows that any maximal matching is a 2-approximation of a maximum matching and also a 2-approximation of a minimum maximal matching.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] This inequality is tight: for example, if *G* is a path with 3 edges and 4 vertices, the size of a minimum maximal matching is 1 and the size of a maximum matching is 2.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] A generating function of the number of *k*-edge matchings in a graph is called a matching polynomial.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] Let *G* be a graph and *mk* be the number of *k*-edge matchings.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] where *n* is the number of vertices in the graph.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] Each type has its uses; for more information see the article on matching polynomials.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] A fundamental problem in combinatorial optimization is finding a *maximum matching*.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] This problem has various algorithms for different classes of graphs.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] In an *unweighted bipartite graph*, the optimization problem is to find a maximum cardinality matching.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] The problem is solved by the Hopcroft-Karp algorithm in time *O*(√*V**E*) time, and there are more efficient randomized algorithms, approximation algorithms, and algorithms for special classes of graphs such as bipartite planar graphs, as described in the main article.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] In a *weighted* *bipartite graph,* the optimization problem is to find a maximum-weight matching; a dual problem is to find a minimum-weight matching.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] This problem is often called **maximum weighted bipartite matching**, or the **assignment problem**.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] The Hungarian algorithm solves the assignment problem and it was one of the beginnings of combinatorial optimization algorithms.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] It uses a modified shortest path search in the augmenting path algorithm.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] If the Bellman–Ford algorithm is used for this step, the running time of the Hungarian algorithm becomes $O(V^{2}E)$ , or the edge cost can be shifted with a potential to achieve $O(V^{2}\log {V}+VE)$ running time with the Dijkstra algorithm and Fibonacci heap.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] In a *non-bipartite weighted graph*, the problem of **maximum weight matching** can be solved in time $O(V^{2}E)$ using Edmonds' blossom algorithm.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] A maximal matching can be found with a simple greedy algorithm.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] A maximum matching is also a maximal matching, and hence it is possible to find a *largest* maximal matching in polynomial time.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] It is also possible to find a maximum matching with the use of fast matrix multiplication algorithms in the time $O({n^{\omega }})$ for $~2.37\leq \omega <3$ .
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] However, no polynomial-time algorithm is known for finding a **minimum maximal matching**, that is, a maximal matching that contains the *smallest* possible number of edges.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] A maximal matching with *k* edges is an edge dominating set with *k* edges.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] Conversely, if we are given a minimum edge dominating set with *k* edges, we can construct a maximal matching with *k* edges in polynomial time.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] Therefore, the problem of finding a minimum maximal matching is essentially equal to the problem of finding a minimum edge dominating set.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] Both of these two optimization problems are known to be NP-hard; the decision versions of these problems are classical examples of NP-complete problems.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] Both problems can be approximated within factor 2 in polynomial time: simply find an arbitrary maximal matching *M*.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] The number of matchings in a graph is known as the Hosoya index of the graph.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] It is #P-complete to compute this quantity, even for bipartite graphs.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] It is also #P-complete to count perfect matchings, even in bipartite graphs, because computing the permanent of an arbitrary 0–1 matrix (another #P-complete problem) is the same as computing the number of perfect matchings in the bipartite graph having the given matrix as its biadjacency matrix.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] However, there exists a fully polynomial time randomized approximation scheme for counting the number of bipartite matchings.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] A remarkable theorem of Kasteleyn states that the number of perfect matchings in a planar graph can be computed exactly in polynomial time via the FKT algorithm.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] The number of perfect matchings in a complete graph *K**n* (with *n* even) is given by the double factorial (*n* − 1)!!.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] The numbers of matchings in complete graphs, without constraining the matchings to be perfect, are given by the telephone numbers.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] The number of perfect matchings in a graph is also known as the hafnian of its adjacency matrix.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] One of the basic problems in matching theory is to find in a given graph all edges that may be extended to a maximum matching in the graph (such edges are called maximally matchable edges, or **allowed** edges).
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] The problem of developing an online algorithm for matching was first considered by Richard M.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] Karp, Umesh Vazirani, and Vijay Vazirani in 1990.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] In the online setting, nodes on one side of the bipartite graph ("clients") arrive one at a time and must either be immediately matched to the other side of the graph ("servers") or discarded.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] This is a natural generalization of the secretary problem and has applications to online ad auctions.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] A simple greedy algorithm is 1/2-competitive.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] For the unweighted maximization case with a random arrival model, Karp, Vazirani and Vazirani gave a randomized algorithm that attains a competitive ratio of 0.632.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/matching-graph-theory] The problem was also studied in a model where clients may switch servers in order to improve the matching, and the goal is to economize on the number of switches while achieving a maximum matching.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/maximum-cardinality-matching] In graph theory, a **maximum-cardinality matching** is a special kind of subgraph useful in many computational contexts.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/maximum-cardinality-matching] Given a graph G, a matching is a subgraph where no two edges share a vertex.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/maximum-cardinality-matching] The cardinality of the matching is the number of edges in the subgraph, and the maximum cardinality is the largest number of edges a matching can contain.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/maximum-cardinality-matching] A matching for a given graph is a **maximum-cardinality matching** if its cardinality is this maximum cardinality.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/maximum-cardinality-matching] If we think of each edge as "covering" the vertices it connects exactly once, then a maximal matching is also the largest non-overlapping cover of the graph.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/maximum-cardinality-matching] If all the vertices are covered, we call it a perfect matching.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/maximum-cardinality-matching] For finite graphs, a maximum-cardinality matching always exists, but is not usually unique.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/maximum-cardinality-matching] The cardinality of the matching is never more than half the number of vertices and also never more than the number of edges.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/maximum-cardinality-matching] An important special case of the maximum-cardinality matching problem is when G is a bipartite graph representing a binary relation, whose vertices V are partitioned between left vertices in X and right vertices in Y, and edges in E always connect a left vertex to a right vertex.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/maximum-cardinality-matching] In this case, the problem can be efficiently solved with simpler algorithms than in the general case.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/maximum-cardinality-matching] The calculation of a **maximum matching** for a given graph is a fundamental task in computational graph theory.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/maximum-cardinality-matching] There are nonconstructive characterization theorems for the size of a maximum matching.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/maximum-cardinality-matching] This article is about computation of maximum matchings.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/maximum-cardinality-matching] The simplest way to compute a maximum-cardinality matching is to follow the Ford–Fulkerson algorithm.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/maximum-cardinality-matching] This algorithm solves the more general problem of computing the maximum flow.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/maximum-cardinality-matching] A bipartite graph (*X* + *Y*, *E*) can be converted to a flow network as follows.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/maximum-cardinality-matching] Since each edge in the network has integral capacity, there exists a maximum flow where all flows are integers; these integers must be either 0 or 1 since the all capacities are 1.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/maximum-cardinality-matching] Each integral flow defines a matching in which an edge is in the matching if and only if its flow is 1.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/maximum-cardinality-matching] The Ford–Fulkerson algorithm proceeds by repeatedly finding an augmenting path from some *x* ∈ *X* to some *y* ∈ Y and updating the matching M by taking the symmetric difference of that path with M (assuming such a path exists).
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/maximum-cardinality-matching] As each path can be found in *O*(*E*) time, the running time is *O*(*VE*), and the maximum matching consists of the edges of E that carry flow from X to Y.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/maximum-cardinality-matching] An improvement to this algorithm is given by the more elaborate Hopcroft–Karp algorithm, which searches for multiple augmenting paths simultaneously.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/maximum-cardinality-matching] This algorithm runs in $O({\sqrt {V}}E)$ time.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/maximum-cardinality-matching] The blossom algorithm finds a maximum-cardinality matching in general (not necessarily bipartite) graphs.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/maximum-cardinality-matching] A better performance of *O*(√*V**E*) for general graphs, matching the performance of the Hopcroft–Karp algorithm on bipartite graphs, can be achieved with the much more complicated algorithm of Micali and Vazirani.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/maximum-cardinality-matching] The same bound was achieved by an algorithm by Blum and an algorithm by Gabow and Tarjan.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/maximum-cardinality-matching] An alternative approach uses randomization and is based on the fast matrix multiplication algorithm.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/maximum-cardinality-matching] This gives a randomized algorithm for general graphs with complexity $O(V^{2.372})$ .
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/maximum-cardinality-matching] This is better in theory for sufficiently dense graphs, but in practice the algorithm is slower.
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/maximum-cardinality-matching] Other algorithms for the task are reviewed by Duan and Pettie (see Table I).
[src:hopcroft-karp-matching/maximum-cardinality-matching] In terms of approximation algorithms, they also point out that the blossom algorithm and the algorithms by Micali and Vazirani can be seen as approximation algorithms running in linear time for any fixed error bound.
